      <p>Transfer duty, which most Australians still call stamp duty, is a state tax paid by the buyer on the purchase of residential property in Queensland. The seller does not pay it, and in most transactions it does not appear directly in any negotiation. But sellers who understand how transfer duty works, how much their likely buyers are paying, and where the key thresholds and concessions sit will make better-informed decisions about pricing and strategy, particularly in Brisbane's inner-east market where properties regularly transact between $900,000 and $2 million.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">How Queensland transfer duty is calculated</h2>
      <p>Queensland uses a tiered rate structure. On a standard residential purchase with no concessions, duty is calculated on progressive bands of the purchase price. At lower price points the effective rate is modest, but as the price rises the marginal rate increases, and at prices above $1 million the duty bill becomes a material number that buyers must fund in addition to their deposit.</p>

      <p>As a rough indication of the scale: a buyer purchasing a property at $1 million in Queensland pays approximately $38,000 in transfer duty. At $1.5 million, the bill is approximately $62,000. At $2 million, it is approximately $87,000. These figures are approximate and can change with Queensland Budget updates, but the order of magnitude is consistent: by the time a buyer is purchasing a family home in Camp Hill, Morningside, or Coorparoo at current inner-east prices, their transfer duty liability alone is often equivalent to a year of mortgage repayments at moderate interest rates.</p>

      <p>This matters for sellers because transfer duty must generally be paid in cash from the buyer's own funds, often within 30 days of contract. It cannot be borrowed as part of the mortgage in most circumstances. A buyer who has a 10% deposit saved plus their borrowing capacity funded is still required to find the duty on top of those funds. For buyers who have not accounted for this carefully, it creates real pressure on the total purchase budget.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">First home buyer concessions and what they mean for sellers</h2>
      <p>Queensland offers a first home buyer concession on transfer duty for eligible purchasers buying a home to live in. The concession is substantial at lower price points, phasing out as the purchase price increases and generally becoming negligible or zero above a certain threshold (currently around $550,000 for the full concession, though these thresholds are adjusted periodically).</p>

      <p>For sellers of properties priced above the concession threshold, the first home buyer pool is effectively constrained. A buyer who qualifies for the concession is motivated to stay within the price range where it applies. Once a property is priced beyond that range, first home buyers require significantly more upfront cash to fund both their deposit and their duty liability. This does not remove first home buyers from the market at higher price points, but it does thin the pool and affects how aggressively they can compete.</p>

      <p>For sellers in the $700,000 to $900,000 price range, this dynamic is particularly relevant. Properties at the upper end of that band may attract first home buyers who are stretching their budget; properties just above it may see those buyers drop out entirely. Understanding where your property sits relative to that threshold, and how many genuine first home buyers are in your likely buyer pool, helps you and your agent calibrate expectations about competition and the likely buyer profile.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">How duty thresholds affect price sensitivity</h2>
      <p>Buyers and their advisors are aware of the duty structure and sometimes use it in negotiations. A buyer looking at two comparable properties, one priced at $999,000 and one at $1,010,000, will pay meaningfully different amounts of duty even though the gap in purchase price is small. In a tightly competitive market this rarely drives behaviour, but in a softer market where a buyer has genuine choice, it can affect which property they pursue first.</p>

      <p>More practically, duty thresholds explain some of the price clustering you see in the inner-east market. Round-number pricing at $1 million, $1.5 million, and $2 million is common, partly because these are psychologically significant numbers for buyers and partly because the duty calculations at those points are well understood. Pricing a property just above a threshold can introduce resistance from buyers who are right at the edge of their total purchase budget, including duty. Your agent should understand these dynamics and factor them into your pricing strategy and your auction or expression-of-interest guide.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">Foreign buyer duty surcharges and what they mean for seller strategy</h2>
      <p>Queensland imposes an additional transfer duty surcharge on foreign buyers, currently 8% of the purchase price on top of the standard duty rates. For a property at $1.5 million, this represents an additional $120,000 in upfront costs for a foreign buyer compared to a domestic buyer paying standard duty. This surcharge significantly reduces the competitive position of foreign buyers at almost every price point, meaning that in most inner-east Brisbane campaigns, the effective buyer pool is predominantly domestic owner-occupiers and Australian-resident investors.</p>

      <p>This is useful context for sellers who might wonder whether their property attracts international interest. While foreign buyers are not absent from the Brisbane market, the surcharge creates a substantial disincentive that limits their practical participation in most standard residential transactions. Sellers should not build their pricing strategy around foreign buyer competition unless their agent can demonstrate specific evidence of it in comparable sales.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">Why understanding buyer costs makes sellers better negotiators</h2>
      <p>The most practical takeaway for sellers is this: the buyer's total acquisition cost is the purchase price plus transfer duty plus legal fees plus any building and pest inspection costs plus their mortgage application and valuation costs. At $1.5 million in Brisbane's inner east, a buyer's total out-of-pocket cost before they receive keys is typically in the range of $1.57 million to $1.59 million, depending on their loan structure. Their negotiating headroom is constrained by that total, not just by the purchase price in isolation.</p>

      <p>When a buyer pushes hard on price in the final stages of a negotiation, they are often managing a real budget constraint that includes costs beyond the headline number. A seller who understands this can negotiate more precisely. Rather than reading every price push as evidence that the buyer is not serious, a seller who understands the buyer's total cost picture can make better-informed decisions about when to hold their position and when a small concession on price might close a deal that is genuinely at the buyer's limit.</p>

      <p>This is not about sympathy for buyers. It is about understanding the market you are selling into well enough to negotiate effectively within it. Transfer duty is one of the more significant costs buyers carry into your transaction, and the more clearly you understand its effect on their behaviour, the sharper your decision-making will be.</p>

